<br>
I welcome any GL to post it to their own websites.<br>
<br>
My Experience on Dragon Raids.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 Well I have now attended two Dragon Raids, which have both been a success. We have slain Lord Nagafen and Lady Vox in a relatively short period of time. <br>
<br>
Both of these raids were run by Raid Commander Haemish. This man knows what he is doing. Though gruff at times, he has the process down pact, to not only make the raid successful but to minimize deaths the best he can.<br>
<br>
The first thing you should know is that there are minimum levels, which is 40 for all classes, except true casters which is 45. There is a reason for this. The dragons don't like you, they take you down quickly. <br>
<br>
The second is you need resistance gear. Again there is a reason. The more your resistance is, the better chances of your survival. Lady Vox requires a minimum of 70 Cold and 70 magic (unbuffed). Now you can still attend, but be prepared to die. <br>
<br>
Sign-ups begin at the time that is posted. Groups are assigned usually an hour later. The more you straggle in getting there, the more we have all waited around for you. Standing beside the people who are taking in the sign-ins, drinking, doing emotes, casting spells, etc. creates major lag. This delays the process. So step aside and move away a bit, so that they can get their job done. By the way, don't bother buffing yourself, it's a waste of time and mana, until you have been assigned to a group. You need to bring 50pp for these raids, which you will give to your group leader once assigned. Clerics, Necromancers and Enchanters are exempt. This fee is to cover reagent expenses (coffins, peridots, etc), which are required during raids for either buffing or recovery.<br>
<br>
If you have been asked not to talk in /ooc or /shout, then abide by that. They are trying to focus on the deed at hand, which is to get everyone signed in and the groups organized as fast as possible. These dragon raids run from 4-6 hours long from start up time. Know that going in, and don't complain.<br>
<br>
They will announce who are the leaders of the raid. The only people who can talk to them is either your group leader, or the back-up group leader, absolutely no one else. If you have been designated as the looter, then you may only speak with the assigned loot coordinator for the raid. <br>
<br>
Once you have been assigned in a group, your group leader will appoint a looter and a back-up group leader in case of their link death. Write down who is in your group. If they haven't told you what your responsibility is within a reasonable amount of time, then ask. Once in your group, and you have your assignment, put the appropriate spells up that you need. If you don't know which ones, ask. Don't feel you need to put 8 in since there are 8 spots. Only put in those you need. <br>
<br>
Groups are then called in one or two at a time. KNOW YOUR GROUP NUMBER. Follow your leader closely. If it's your first raid, don't be embarrassed to tell your group leader. If you have questions, ask your group leader. If your group leader does not know the answer, they will contact the raid leaders for an answer. DON'T WANDER. You are risking everyone's life if you do so.<br>
