<br>
To reduce lag, turn sky off, particles to low, clip plane to far left, turn numerous chats of (auction, guildsay), and turn off bard song. You should also type in /serverfilter on. (Sorry I haven't a clue what this is for, but it works).<br>
<br>
From this point on, no one but the raid commander, the loot coordinator and the raid leaders, are to use /shout or /ooc or emotes. DO NOT DRINK on raids, until the dragon has been slain. You will have been advised as to who the assists are, make sure you have a hotkey set up as follows &quot;/assist (secondary's name), then on the next line /assist (primary's name).<br>
<br>
Once you have worked your way in and everything has been slain in the path to the dragon, you will be asked to camp out immediately and then return. Do what you are told, this is done so we will not be aggro'd. When you camp back in, find your group leader and get re-invited. (Hence why you wrote it down.)<br>
<br>
Next there becomes a buffing line of about 12 - 14 buffs. Each class will be called one at a time, to get their buffs. This process is slow and tedious but necessary for success. Go thru the line as quickly as possible and log. You will be told what chat room to go to. Don't straggle in getting there. The reason for this, is so everyone holds their buffs, when going in for the fight. The raid commander will show up and start to explain the process as to how the dragon will get taken down. Wait until the commander has fully spoken, before asking questions. Everything will be answered, when given enough time. By the way, a triage line is the healing line. The raid commander will advise who goes into the room first, usually starting with the warriors. Pure casters are not to cast until the dragon has been taken down to 70% or less of their health. You then nuke continually. A healing line is created, usually of clerics, shamans and druids (that are under level 50). Druids over 50 are nukers. <br>
<br>
The fight......Each class runs in and starts pounding and nuking. The raid commander will tell you how it's best done, prior to entering as well as which spells are best. If you hit 50 health run to the healing line. Don't be a hero.<br>
<br>
The healing line....This is usually set up just outside the lair. Run towards the healing line, (at this point you should have a hotkey set up &quot;/shout Mirithal coming in for a heal&quot;. As the healer in the group for Mirithal, start clicking on the heal, once he is in range it will hit him. Don't wait until the person stands in front of you. We want to heal them quick and send them back into battle.<br>
<br>
**I will definitely be re-writing this, as there are corrections that need to be made, but until I get time, this is a good start**<br>
